A close parallel will, however, be found in the famous passage in Bracton f. yb, where he dscusses, not the condition of English landowners after the conquest, but that of certain tenants within mauors of royal demesue. Bracton tells much the same story; these tenacis, free at the conquest, were ejected by their uerv lords, restored in a worse condition, and provided hythe crown with a legal remedy. These tenants also were of two kinds, those who held with a special agreement, aud those who had none. Bracton’s account, again, is a legal theory of history rather than history. The problem suggested by this parallel is double; firstly, are the two authors thinking of the same set of facts? aud secondly, was Bracton acquainted with this passage? The second question is one for commentatore on Bracton ; but in answer to the first it may be pointed out that it is almost incredible that e theory which Bracton applies to an exceptional class of small holders on the royal demesue can be equally applicable when extended to every landholder in the country. lt may be suggested that the Dialogus has set out to tell one story and ended by telling another.
